00:33.784 --> 00:36.411
One nation under God, indivisible,

00:36.578 --> 00:39.288
with liberty and justice for all.

00:39.456 --> 00:42.542
GIRL:
I pledge allegiance to the flag

00:42.710 --> 00:45.253
of the United States of America

00:45.421 --> 00:49.132
and to republic
for which it stands.

00:49.299 --> 00:53.136
One nation under God, indivisible,

00:53.303 --> 00:55.847
with liberty and justice for all.

00:56.014 --> 00:58.307
BOY 2:
I pledge allegiance to the flag

00:58.475 --> 01:00.476
of United States of America

01:00.644 --> 01:03.730
and to the republic
for which it stands.

01:03.897 --> 01:07.483
One nation under God, indivisible,

01:07.651 --> 01:08.860
with liberty...

01:09.027 --> 01:12.363
KIDS:
And justice for all.

01:12.531 --> 01:15.199
[♪♪♪]

03:37.509 --> 03:39.635
[POLICE SIREN WAILING
IN DISTANCE]

03:52.232 --> 03:54.066
COP:
Take your wig off.

03:54.902 --> 03:56.652
Take your wig off.

04:00.949 --> 04:02.366
[CAMERA CLICKS]

04:02.826 --> 04:04.869
Turn and face the wall.

04:05.621 --> 04:07.872
This way.
Turn and face the wall.

04:08.040 --> 04:09.957
Face the wall.

04:12.002 --> 04:13.753
All right. That's it.

04:20.010 --> 04:21.802
PRISONER 1:
Are you a natural blond?

04:21.970 --> 04:23.012
[PRISONERS WHISTLING]

04:23.180 --> 04:24.889
PRISONER 2:
Chicken delight. He deliver.

04:25.057 --> 04:28.059
PRISONER 3:
Don't put that in here.
Chick ain't my type.

04:28.226 --> 04:30.436
PRISONER 4:
Easy, easy. That's my wife
you're talking about.

04:30.604 --> 04:33.105
She here
for our conjugal visit.

04:33.273 --> 04:36.192
Come over here
and let daddy show you
what he got in his pants.

04:36.360 --> 04:39.153
PRISONER 1:
Shit, she got the same thing
up under her skirt

04:39.321 --> 04:42.198
that you got in your pants.
GUARD 1: Come on. Hold it, hold it.

04:42.366 --> 04:44.784
Come on, we got a lady here.

04:44.952 --> 04:48.329
Okay, Agee. You got any
concealed weapons that
they didn't find up front?

04:48.497 --> 04:49.872
PRISONER 2:
He got something concealed.

04:50.040 --> 04:52.583
PRISONER 3: But it ain't no weapon.
PRISONERS: Ha, ha, ha.

04:52.751 --> 04:54.543
What do you say you strip
to make sure?

04:54.711 --> 04:55.962
Whoo!

04:57.422 --> 05:00.591
[PRISONERS HOOTING
AND WHISTLING]

05:14.231 --> 05:17.108
PRISONER 4:
A star is born.

05:17.401 --> 05:19.402
[PRISONERS HOOTING
AND WHISTLING]

05:19.736 --> 05:21.821
GUARD 2:
Hey, Kirkland. Watch your hands.

05:23.115 --> 05:24.740
PRISONER 1:
Hey, what's that?

05:27.536 --> 05:30.579
GUARD 2:
Come on, Kirkland. Let's go.

05:30.747 --> 05:34.291
PRISONER 2:
Hey, dude. Wow, look at that.

05:35.669 --> 05:38.754
PRISONER 3:
I say, hey, man.
Make a phone call for me, man.

05:38.922 --> 05:41.757
PRISONER 4:
Hey, man, don't run off now,
big shot.

05:42.050 --> 05:44.468
[PRISONERS CHEERING
AND WHISTLING]

05:46.013 --> 05:48.848
PRISONER 1:
All right. All right.

05:53.228 --> 05:55.354
Where the hell is he?

05:57.024 --> 05:59.358
What do you mean, he's in jail?

06:00.110 --> 06:02.403
My lawyer's in jail?

06:03.238 --> 06:05.156
Contempt of court?

06:05.323 --> 06:06.615
He's too goddamn emotional.

06:06.783 --> 06:09.201
Get him. I've had a car accident.

06:09.369 --> 06:11.787
I haven't left the scene
of the accident, I'm in it!

06:11.955 --> 06:15.624
DISPATCHER [ON RADIO]:
Unit 4-Adam. Be advised,
no record, no warrant.

06:15.792 --> 06:18.627
Can't you hear the confusion around
me? You hear this noise?

06:18.795 --> 06:22.465
Firemen trying to get me out
of the car. I'm trapped
because some son...

06:22.632 --> 06:24.800
FIREMAN 1:
Could you move back?
We're gonna try and get you out.

06:24.968 --> 06:26.719
I'm on the phone.
FIREMAN 2: Just a minute.

06:26.887 --> 06:30.723
Keep it down, for chrissake.
I'm trying... Goddamn it.

06:30.891 --> 06:33.225
Listen, I want you to tell
Arthur to get over here.

06:33.393 --> 06:35.311
I'm on the... Where are we?
Eager Street.

06:35.479 --> 06:37.188
The Eager Street ex...

06:37.355 --> 06:39.774
Just tell him to get over here.
You can't miss it.

06:40.776 --> 06:44.653
KILEY:
I understand you took a swing
at Judge Fleming. Is that true?

06:45.405 --> 06:48.991
Hey, Kiley. Why don't you
do something about
that kid in there?

06:49.159 --> 06:50.826
Put him someplace else?

06:50.994 --> 06:53.579
Oh, they're just having
some fun with him, that's all.

06:53.747 --> 06:55.331
Fun?

06:55.499 --> 06:57.291
Well, sometimes
the boys get bored.

06:57.459 --> 06:58.542
[PRISONERS HOOTING]

06:58.710 --> 07:01.295
With you,
it's still new and exciting.

07:02.172 --> 07:03.172
Sign here.

07:05.759 --> 07:08.427
Why don't you ease up
on the judge?

07:10.347 --> 07:12.181
He's your kind of guy,
huh?

07:13.225 --> 07:15.726
Yeah, Fleming's a tough man.

07:15.894 --> 07:17.853
Hates scum
almost as much as we do.

07:19.606 --> 07:20.856
[GROANS]

07:21.650 --> 07:23.859
Good morning,
Mr. Kirkland.

07:46.258 --> 07:49.802
Carl.
Yeah, Arthur.

07:51.388 --> 07:53.639
Come on. Are you all right?

07:53.807 --> 07:56.392
I want you to sue the son
of a bitch who did this to me.

07:56.560 --> 07:58.727
Every cent he's got.
Every nickel.

07:58.895 --> 08:01.021
Thank God I can walk.
Carl, are you all right?

08:01.189 --> 08:02.857
Disappear.

08:03.400 --> 08:06.318
Why don't you wait...
She wasn't hurt, nothing in the report.

08:06.486 --> 08:09.530
Why don't you wait in the car.
No need for the wife to know.

08:09.698 --> 08:11.866
All right.
After all, I was your first.

08:12.033 --> 08:14.201
You know, Arthur?
I was your first client.

08:14.369 --> 08:15.578
You broke cherry on me.

08:15.745 --> 08:17.746
Not the time to go
down memory lane, Carl.

08:17.914 --> 08:20.749
Let's just get you to the hospital,
get you checked out.

08:20.917 --> 08:22.251
Lie back.
You are the best.

08:22.419 --> 08:24.420
Get every nickel,
then have him put away.

08:24.588 --> 08:26.714
I'll see he gets
the death penalty, Carl.

08:26.882 --> 08:29.091
Lie back, sir.
Death is okay too.

08:29.259 --> 08:31.427
Jesus, you stink.
Somebody piss on you?

08:31.595 --> 08:32.678
Get him out
of here.

08:32.846 --> 08:34.847
Make sure nobody uses
my car phone.

08:35.015 --> 08:37.975
I'm in a hospital,
some jerk calls Rome.

08:38.143 --> 08:40.436
You son of a bitch! You lunatic!

08:40.604 --> 08:42.938
Carl. Carl, you're
gonna have a stroke.

08:43.106 --> 08:45.649
You'll have to deal
with my lawyer!

08:45.817 --> 08:49.236
The death penalty!
You'll die for this. He's the best.

08:49.404 --> 08:50.946
It's not even my car.

08:51.114 --> 08:53.949
Carl. Carl. Carl.

08:55.118 --> 08:57.536
I got a terrible headache.
You'll be all right.

08:57.704 --> 09:00.122
I'll call you at the hospital.

09:00.790 --> 09:02.291
What about this guy here?

09:02.459 --> 09:04.460
He says he's all right.

09:05.795 --> 09:08.255
I mean, it's a friend's car.

09:08.423 --> 09:11.508
I just borrowed it for the night,
and now how am I gonna tell him?

09:11.676 --> 09:13.469
I think you should
go to the hospital.

09:13.637 --> 09:15.971
Well, I'm okay, but the car...
I know. I know.

09:16.139 --> 09:17.890
Let me take you over
to the hospital.

09:18.058 --> 09:20.267
My horoscope said
it was gonna be a great day.

09:20.435 --> 09:22.311
And look what happened.
You'll be fine.

09:23.146 --> 09:25.606
[♪♪♪]

09:45.710 --> 09:48.504
No, it's not gonna
be that way this time.

09:54.469 --> 09:56.220
Look at me
when I'm talking to you.

09:56.388 --> 09:58.681
DA's willing to go two years,
one year probation.

09:58.848 --> 10:00.849
That's a lot of fucking time, man.

10:01.017 --> 10:03.018
Okay? Hi, Artie.

10:03.186 --> 10:06.188
I ain't kissing nobody's ass.
I'm not asking you to kiss it.

10:06.356 --> 10:09.191
Just give it a little pat.

10:09.359 --> 10:12.528
Arthur.

10:12.696 --> 10:14.321
Excuse me.
Yes?

10:14.489 --> 10:16.865
Hold it, Wenke.
Where are you going?

10:17.033 --> 10:18.325
Bathroom.
Go home.

10:18.493 --> 10:19.576
No.
Go home and change.

10:19.744 --> 10:20.869
No.
You look like shit.

10:21.037 --> 10:23.580
What would you say
if I walked into court like that?

10:23.748 --> 10:26.333
Arthur? What would...?
Arthur, what would you say?

10:28.753 --> 10:30.587
I don't want
to keep harping on this,

10:30.755 --> 10:33.257
but the ethics committee's
checking up on everyone.

10:33.425 --> 10:35.134
Please,
you gotta watch it.

10:35.302 --> 10:36.343
Okay, I'll watch it.

10:36.511 --> 10:39.096
Last week, two lawyers were
disbarred on minor charges.

10:39.264 --> 10:41.932
You run around, get thrown into
jail on contempt of court.

10:42.100 --> 10:44.059
Fleming got me crazy.
You push Fleming

10:44.227 --> 10:45.894
on that McCullaugh thing,

10:46.062 --> 10:48.314
there's gonna be big trouble,
I'm telling you.

10:48.481 --> 10:51.483
McCullaugh's innocent,
and I can't get
that goddamn Fleming

10:51.651 --> 10:53.527
to even look
at the evidence, Jay.

10:53.695 --> 10:56.363
What do you want me to do?
You don't threaten the judge.

10:56.531 --> 10:59.158
You don't threaten the judge!

11:06.291 --> 11:09.084
You do me
a personal favor?

11:09.252 --> 11:11.337
Put this on.

11:14.841 --> 11:16.175
Chanel something.

11:16.343 --> 11:19.053
I got Fleming
first thing this morning.

11:19.220 --> 11:21.138
Give him my love.

11:22.599 --> 11:25.100
That tie, I like it.

11:25.268 --> 11:27.853
It's Fleming's favorite color.

11:28.938 --> 11:31.190
[BOTH LAUGHING]

11:32.734 --> 11:34.360
BAILIFF:
All rise.

11:34.527 --> 11:37.279
Criminal court of Baltimore City
is now in session.

11:37.447 --> 11:40.616
The Honorable Henry T. Fleming
presiding.

11:41.743 --> 11:43.077
Be seated.

11:43.244 --> 11:45.496
If Your Honor please,
for the first matter,

11:45.663 --> 11:50.167
the state would call
case number 577-46898,

11:50.335 --> 11:52.044
State v. Robert Wenke.

11:52.212 --> 11:56.131
FLEMING:
Mr. Wenke, may I ask you
to step forward, please?

12:01.346 --> 12:04.473
And how many times have you been
before the bench, Mr. Wenke?

12:04.641 --> 12:05.891
Three times, Your Honor.

12:08.269 --> 12:12.314
Once for assault, once for arson,
once for grand larceny.

12:12.482 --> 12:15.984
And now we have
indecent exposure.

12:16.152 --> 12:17.486
What's the matter, Mr. Wenke?

12:17.654 --> 12:19.780
Can't you decide what you
wanna be when you grow up?

12:19.948 --> 12:21.156
[PEOPLE LAUGHING]

12:21.324 --> 12:23.117
Got anything to say?

12:27.038 --> 12:28.497
Yes, Your Honor.

12:28.665 --> 12:30.332
I'm a loyal Colts fan.

12:30.708 --> 12:33.001
[PEOPLE LAUGHING]

12:38.633 --> 12:42.177
You are also a revolting,
despicable, scum of the earth

12:42.345 --> 12:45.013
who should be taken out
and squashed like a cockroach.

12:45.181 --> 12:47.933
Judge, I object. My client
has not been found guilty yet.

12:48.101 --> 12:50.436
You're absolutely right, counselor.

12:50.603 --> 12:52.813
Let's see, it's now 9:40.

12:52.981 --> 12:55.357
At 9:41 he will be guilty.

13:00.029 --> 13:02.114
I find the defendant,
Ronald Wenke, guilty.

13:02.282 --> 13:04.450
Sentence to be imposed
at a later time.

13:06.369 --> 13:09.371
Your Honor, I would request
that Mr. Wenke's bail be continued.

13:09.539 --> 13:11.623
Bail is revoked.
Thank you, Your Honor.

13:11.791 --> 13:16.837
PROSECUTOR:
If Your Honor please, the state will now
call indictment number 577-46899...

13:17.005 --> 13:20.048
That was good. Very good
work. I wanna thank you
for your counsel.

13:20.216 --> 13:22.301
Very nice. Colts fan.
I need Colts?

13:22.469 --> 13:24.178
That's terrific, Wenke.

13:24.345 --> 13:25.679
You do know.

13:25.847 --> 13:27.556
The big white house.

13:27.724 --> 13:29.766
You know, with the fat
columns out in front?

13:29.934 --> 13:31.810
On Greenway Avenue.

13:33.188 --> 13:36.023
Guess how much
that house is worth
on the market today?

13:36.191 --> 13:39.026
I don't know.
Take a guess.

13:39.736 --> 13:41.820
Seven million.

13:41.988 --> 13:44.907
Two-hundred and forty-three
thousand dollars.

13:45.074 --> 13:47.868
Now, that's some nut
I've got, huh?

13:48.244 --> 13:51.497
That's okay. I get enough
accident cases this year,
I'll be all right.

13:51.664 --> 13:53.916
Maybe I ought to start
throwing out banana peels.

13:54.083 --> 13:58.378
Listen, recess is almost over and all
I've got left is this illegal lottery case...

13:58.546 --> 14:00.214
Did you know that there's a guy

14:00.381 --> 14:02.257
eating something off your table?
Huh?

14:02.425 --> 14:04.718
The guy you're prosecuting?
Yeah?

14:04.886 --> 14:06.512
He's eating the lottery tickets.

14:08.932 --> 14:10.349
Holy shit.

14:10.517 --> 14:12.976
Gibson, get the hell away...
Get out of there.

14:13.144 --> 14:15.812
GIBSON: Leave me alone.
Don't swallow.

14:15.980 --> 14:18.398
You son of a bitch.
ARTHUR: My client.

14:18.566 --> 14:20.567
MAN 1: Give me that. Don't swallow.
ARTHUR: My client.

14:20.735 --> 14:22.444
MAN 1:
Spit it out.

14:22.779 --> 14:26.448
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

14:36.000 --> 14:37.459
[WOMAN SCREAMS]

14:37.919 --> 14:39.628
Gentlemen,

14:39.796 --> 14:43.340
need I remind you,
you are in a court of law?

14:53.059 --> 14:55.978
Now, let's proceed
in an orderly fashion.

15:03.987 --> 15:06.446
What the hell are you doing?

15:15.039 --> 15:17.165
Does the defense have
anything further to add?

15:18.918 --> 15:20.794
Your Honor, it's, uh...

15:22.046 --> 15:25.007
I guess I should, uh,
request a recess

15:25.174 --> 15:27.593
so that my client
could get something to eat.

15:27.760 --> 15:29.678
He's obviously very hungry.

15:29.846 --> 15:31.805
[PEOPLE LAUGHING]

15:35.226 --> 15:38.562
ARTHUR:
My client, McCullaugh,
could I see him for a minute?

15:38.730 --> 15:40.731
GUARD 1:
Sure, Mr. Kirkland.

15:40.898 --> 15:42.691
Put your hand out.

15:43.818 --> 15:45.694
JEFF:
Hey, Mr. Kirkland. What happened?

15:45.862 --> 15:48.739
I just want to reaffirm
what I said to you yesterday.

15:48.906 --> 15:51.825
We're gonna get you out.
I know you're trying, Mr. Kirkland.

15:51.993 --> 15:54.870
But this is crazy, you know?
I know it. I know it.

15:55.038 --> 15:57.706
You told me
you have the evidence
that proves I'm innocent.

15:57.874 --> 16:00.375
It does prove it, doesn't it?
Yes, you're innocent.

16:00.543 --> 16:02.878
Judge Fleming agrees with you?
Right.

16:03.046 --> 16:06.506
If everyone agrees that I'm innocent,
how come I'm going back to jail?

16:06.674 --> 16:08.508
GUARD 2: Roll them.
There's enough proof, Jeff.

16:08.676 --> 16:10.636
It's just the court
won't accept the proof.

16:10.803 --> 16:13.889
Why not?
Well, there's a law...

16:14.057 --> 16:18.018
There's a law which says
that evidence must be submitted

16:18.186 --> 16:20.395
within a certain time period.

16:20.563 --> 16:22.481
And our evidence came in
three days late.

16:22.649 --> 16:24.566
JEFF:
What difference does that make?

16:24.734 --> 16:27.069
What difference does it make
if it came years late?

16:27.236 --> 16:29.571
They got the proof.
They should let me go.

16:29.739 --> 16:31.198
I don't understand this.

16:31.366 --> 16:35.160
That judge who sent me
to jail, he knows I'm innocent.
What's going on?

16:35.328 --> 16:37.663
Jeff, it's just gonna take
a little more time.

16:37.830 --> 16:40.457
Any other judge would have let
you out, but this guy,

16:40.625 --> 16:43.293
he goes by the letter of the law.
I don't understand.

16:43.461 --> 16:46.505
Jeff, I promise...
I promise I'll get you out. I promise.

16:46.673 --> 16:50.300
MAN:
He promises he'll get
you out, buddy, don't worry.

17:01.771 --> 17:03.522
Judge Fleming?

17:05.316 --> 17:07.651
I want to apologize
to you, sir, for my...

17:07.819 --> 17:09.319
My behavior in the courtroom...

17:09.487 --> 17:11.279
I don't want to hear
your apologies.

17:11.446 --> 17:13.531
I don't want to hear
anything you have to say.

17:13.700 --> 17:15.951
That's understandable, sir.
It's just...

17:16.118 --> 17:19.329
It's just I thought that maybe we could
discuss this McCullaugh case.

17:19.497 --> 17:22.249
You know, you and I,
man to man?
Off the record, sir.

17:22.416 --> 17:24.459
If you're gonna try to
make a deal with me,

17:24.627 --> 17:26.461
you might wind up
right back in jail.

17:26.628 --> 17:28.003
A deal? A deal? No, sir.

17:28.172 --> 17:29.965
No, sir, I'm not
trying to make a deal.

17:30.133 --> 17:33.051
I can understand
your strict enforcement
of the statute.

17:33.219 --> 17:36.805
What I can't understand
is my client's constitutional
rights being denied.

17:36.973 --> 17:39.015
Don't quote the law.
My client is innocent.

17:39.183 --> 17:43.061
I don't give a shit
about your client.

18:02.248 --> 18:04.374
Hi.
Hi, Sherry.

18:04.542 --> 18:07.169
Hi, Mr. Kirkland. Nice to see you.
ARTHUR: How are you today?

18:07.336 --> 18:09.087
SHERRY:
He'll be right with you.

18:09.672 --> 18:12.424
Boy, do you look tired.
Coffee, please.

18:12.592 --> 18:14.551
Mrs. Tate wants to talk
to you.

18:14.719 --> 18:18.013
Her son broke his leg again,
neighbor's driveway.

18:18.181 --> 18:22.934
And Bricker wants to know
if your client will settle for $60,000.

18:23.102 --> 18:25.103
Coffee.
You can reach him at the club.

18:25.271 --> 18:27.230
You have three new clients
coming in today.

18:27.398 --> 18:29.649
One's a whiplash,
one's a divorce,

18:29.817 --> 18:32.319
and the other one has something
to do with amnesia.

18:32.487 --> 18:35.530
I don't know what it is.
Arthur, what are you doing?

18:35.698 --> 18:37.365
[CAN HISSING]

18:37.533 --> 18:38.575
It won't foam.

18:38.743 --> 18:40.869
That's because
it's deodorant.

18:41.037 --> 18:43.997
And today is Tuesday,
so don't forget
to visit your grandfather.

18:44.165 --> 18:46.041
And you have to be
back in court at 2: 15.

18:46.209 --> 18:48.293
Coffee, please.

18:49.003 --> 18:50.879
You want some coffee?

18:52.048 --> 18:53.799
Sherry, stay with me today, dear.

18:53.966 --> 18:56.510
I need you today.

19:02.391 --> 19:03.558
Arthur.

19:03.726 --> 19:04.726
[WHISTLES]

19:04.894 --> 19:05.977
Arthur.

19:06.145 --> 19:08.563
Come here. Heh, heh, heh.

19:08.773 --> 19:10.565
Hi, judge.

19:10.733 --> 19:12.984
Are we gonna get together
this weekend, huh?

19:13.152 --> 19:16.822
I don't know. You know,
you're the only one I've
been dating these days.

19:16.989 --> 19:18.073
RAYFORD:
Come on, now.

19:18.241 --> 19:20.867
You promised you'd go
flying with me.

19:21.035 --> 19:23.370
Ugh, I gotta tell you, judge,
you know, I'm not...

19:23.538 --> 19:27.541
I'm not too fond of anything
that takes place off the ground.

19:27.708 --> 19:31.294
Heights. I don't know.
I got a thing about heights.

19:31.462 --> 19:33.755
Come on, this is flying.
It's different.

19:33.923 --> 19:35.382
How high up do you go?

19:35.883 --> 19:37.175
How high up do you wanna go?

19:37.343 --> 19:39.219
Come on, it'll be good for you.

19:39.387 --> 19:42.889
Sure. Besides, it gets...
It gets lonesome up there.

19:43.057 --> 19:44.933
Why don't you take
your wife, judge.

19:45.101 --> 19:47.894
Heh, heh, heh.
Last thing we did together
was get married.

19:48.062 --> 19:50.939
Come on, Arthur.
Now, you promised me, remember?

19:51.107 --> 19:53.108
All right. What time?

19:53.276 --> 19:55.110
Sunday morning, 10:00.

19:55.278 --> 19:56.945
Do you always carry that with you?

19:58.406 --> 20:00.907
There's law and there's order.

20:01.075 --> 20:02.951
And that's order.

20:03.119 --> 20:04.452
Hey, you like egg roll?

20:05.371 --> 20:09.291
Uh, yeah.
Good. Come on, let's get out of here.

20:09.458 --> 20:12.919
Easy, easy, easy.
All right, you got it.
Ha, ha, ha.

20:13.087 --> 20:14.754
Son of a gun.

20:15.965 --> 20:18.717
[♪♪♪]

20:44.368 --> 20:47.287
So it's another week already.

20:47.580 --> 20:50.290
Another week.
I don't know where time goes.

20:50.458 --> 20:53.501
No problems, Grandpa.
Everything all right?

20:54.545 --> 20:56.087
See this one?

20:56.255 --> 20:57.380
Wonderful woman.

20:57.548 --> 21:00.342
I went to her husband's funeral.
Fine man.

21:01.302 --> 21:02.344
Gitel?

21:05.431 --> 21:06.681
Oh, hello, Sam.

21:07.850 --> 21:09.309
How are you?

21:09.477 --> 21:12.270
This is my grandson,
Arthur.

21:12.438 --> 21:14.272
Pleased to meet you.
Good to meet you.

21:14.440 --> 21:18.151
He goes to law school.
I'm a lawyer.

21:18.444 --> 21:21.696
Take my advice.
Don't be in a hurry.

21:23.532 --> 21:25.867
He's a nice-looking boy.

21:26.035 --> 21:27.869
My grandson.

21:28.037 --> 21:29.537
Yes. Heh.

21:35.336 --> 21:38.588
Good to meet you.
Pleased to have met you too.

21:38.756 --> 21:40.298
See you.

21:42.009 --> 21:44.469
So it's been a week.

21:44.637 --> 21:46.888
Yeah, Grandpa, remember?
It's been a week.

21:47.056 --> 21:50.308
Last week, we went for a ride
in the car. Remember?

21:50.518 --> 21:54.270
Oh. That's a good
machine.

21:55.064 --> 21:58.400
Always give signals
when you turn.

21:58.901 --> 22:00.235
Right.
Right.

22:00.403 --> 22:01.987
Left.

22:08.452 --> 22:10.537
WOMAN:
Let's reach for the sky.

22:10.746 --> 22:12.247
So...

22:16.961 --> 22:20.171
Are you a good lawyer?
Heh, heh, heh.

22:20.339 --> 22:22.048
Are you honest?

22:22.842 --> 22:25.010
Well, I don't know.

22:25.177 --> 22:29.806
Being honest doesn't have much
to do with being a lawyer, Grandpa.

22:29.974 --> 22:33.268
If you're not honest,
you got nothing.

22:34.562 --> 22:35.603
Yeah.

22:35.771 --> 22:38.690
Your parents
should see you now.

22:39.942 --> 22:41.860
The hell with them.

22:42.862 --> 22:45.447
They've never cared before,
why are they gonna care now?

22:47.324 --> 22:50.535
They're still your parents.
No.

22:51.579 --> 22:53.455
You raised me.

22:53.622 --> 22:56.291
You're the one that put
me through law school.

22:56.459 --> 22:58.460
You're a wonderful man, Grandpa.

22:58.627 --> 23:00.795
But your son, he's a shit.

23:04.300 --> 23:05.967
He was born with colic.

23:08.888 --> 23:11.097
Sam, I love you.

23:15.728 --> 23:17.645
Look at you.

23:17.813 --> 23:20.315
Filled out like a man.

23:20.733 --> 23:25.570
Soon, you'll look like a lawyer,
and you'll be a lawyer.

23:26.822 --> 23:29.324
I am a lawyer, Sam.

23:29.492 --> 23:31.993
I've been a lawyer for 12 years.

23:32.661 --> 23:35.497
[CHUCKLES]

23:44.507 --> 23:47.258
So it's another week already?

23:53.182 --> 23:55.558
MAN: Do you know Jules Stouffer?
ARTHUR: Yes, I do.

23:55.726 --> 23:58.269
MAN: Client of yours, right?
ARTHUR: Yes.

23:58.437 --> 24:01.981
MAN:
Wasn't he originally
represented by Alvin Burton?

24:02.149 --> 24:03.691
ARTHUR:
Yes, that is correct.

24:03.859 --> 24:05.527
MAN:
Why did he change representation?

24:05.694 --> 24:08.196
Because I handled him on
an aggravated assault charge.

24:08.364 --> 24:10.698
That's my area,
not Burton's area, so...

24:10.866 --> 24:14.494
Did Jules Stouffer express
dissatisfaction with Mr. Burton?

24:14.662 --> 24:16.162
No. Not at all.

24:16.330 --> 24:17.664
Burton's an excellent lawyer.

24:17.832 --> 24:19.541
You're not going after him, are you?

24:19.708 --> 24:22.460
We're not going after anyone,
Mr. Kirkland. We are simply...

24:22.628 --> 24:23.670
Do you
know David...?

24:23.838 --> 24:25.922
We are trying to review
certain accusations

24:26.090 --> 24:28.174
to determine whether or not
they are true.

24:28.342 --> 24:30.718
And to, more or less,
clean our own house.

24:30.886 --> 24:34.180
So please do not overdramatize
these proceedings.

24:34.348 --> 24:38.476
This is not the McCarthy hearings.
Oh. That's a relief.

24:38.644 --> 24:39.894
So you're not gonna ask me:

24:40.062 --> 24:43.523
"Are you now,
or have you ever been, a lawyer?"

24:45.860 --> 24:47.819
That wasn't amusing, Mr. Kirkland.

24:47.987 --> 24:49.404
Do you know David Crebbs?

24:49.864 --> 24:52.323
No, it wasn't, Miss, um...

24:53.742 --> 24:55.827
Packer.
Packer.

24:55.995 --> 24:58.246
This isn't amusing.
It is, however, ridiculous.

24:58.414 --> 25:00.415
Yes. David Crebbs? I know him.

25:00.583 --> 25:03.334
Have you ever seen...?
Is this mike working?

25:06.213 --> 25:07.422
Do you know David Crebbs?

25:07.590 --> 25:09.340
Why are we using microphones?

25:09.508 --> 25:12.135
Why don't we just talk to each other?
We're close enough.

25:12.303 --> 25:14.554
This is a hearing, Mr. Kirkland.

25:15.055 --> 25:17.765
Ah. Yes. It's a hearing.

25:17.933 --> 25:19.267
CRENNA:
Do you know Jules Stouffer?

25:19.435 --> 25:21.686
We've already asked that
question, Mr. Crenna.

25:21.854 --> 25:25.190
Oh, we're through with Stouffer?
How about Alvin Burton?

25:25.357 --> 25:27.817
Do you know David Crebbs?
I already asked that.

25:27.985 --> 25:29.694
What'd he say?

25:29.862 --> 25:30.904
He said, "Yes."

25:31.071 --> 25:33.865
Have you ever seen him
intoxicated in court?

25:34.033 --> 25:37.202
David Crebbs
has a speech impediment.

25:37.369 --> 25:40.371
Now, if you check your records,
you'll see it's there someplace.

25:40.998 --> 25:42.999
No. That's the answer
to your question.

25:43.167 --> 25:46.085
No, he doesn't drink.
Doesn't drink at all.

25:46.545 --> 25:49.297
At this point,
I would just like to say

25:49.465 --> 25:52.800
that what this committee
is doing, in theory,

25:52.968 --> 25:54.886
is highly commendable.

25:55.054 --> 25:59.307
However, in practice, it sucks.

25:59.934 --> 26:02.644
And I am not going to
answer any more questions.

26:11.820 --> 26:14.113
GAIL:
What do you think
we're trying to do in there?

26:16.033 --> 26:17.533
Want a drink?
No.

26:17.701 --> 26:18.868
Whatever you may think,

26:19.036 --> 26:23.414
we are not conducting
some kind of witch hunt.

26:23.582 --> 26:25.124
What are you doing then?

26:25.292 --> 26:27.043
You might not be aware of this,

26:27.211 --> 26:29.504
but there's a lot of
corruption going around

26:29.672 --> 26:31.381
that nobody's
doing anything about.

26:31.548 --> 26:33.508
You think your committee's
doing something?

26:33.676 --> 26:35.093
Yes, I do.

26:35.261 --> 26:39.597
That committee
is a very dangerous farce.

26:40.182 --> 26:43.726
Whoa. Mr. Kirkland.

26:43.894 --> 26:46.271
I spend 14 hours a day
working on that committee.

26:46.438 --> 26:49.274
I don't do it for laughs.
I don't care how many hours.

26:49.441 --> 26:50.942
Understand?
Spend your life.

26:51.110 --> 26:53.111
You know what
you're accomplishing?

26:53.279 --> 26:56.781
If we don't police our own activities,
Ruining the careers of guys

26:56.949 --> 27:00.868
who wipe their ass wrong.
Nothing's gonna happen.

27:06.458 --> 27:08.459
So, what do you think?

27:08.627 --> 27:10.169
About what?

27:10.587 --> 27:12.463
About me.
What do you think?

27:12.631 --> 27:15.049
Think I'm kind of interesting?

27:15.551 --> 27:17.552
Somebody you'd like
to have a drink with?

27:17.720 --> 27:20.638
I think that you're crazy.

27:21.098 --> 27:23.641
Oh. What about Daniels?

27:23.809 --> 27:26.394
Say around 7:30?

27:29.106 --> 27:31.024
I don't think so.

27:31.358 --> 27:32.984
Eight?

27:35.946 --> 27:36.988
Eight-thirty.

27:47.624 --> 27:49.751
All right.

28:00.220 --> 28:03.056
Uh, I'm Arthur Kirkland.
You wanted to see me?

28:04.224 --> 28:05.266
Yeah.

28:11.357 --> 28:14.442
Yeah, my man, Bambi,

28:14.610 --> 28:16.444
ooh, he recommended you
real highly.

28:16.612 --> 28:20.031
He said, "Arthur Kirkland,
he the man to see."

28:20.199 --> 28:22.617
Okay, Ralph. Why don't you
tell me what happened.

28:22.785 --> 28:25.578
It says here in the report
that you were involved in a robbery.

28:25.746 --> 28:28.498
Uh-uh. No, sir.
Uh-uh. No.

28:28.665 --> 28:30.458
See... See, what happened is,

28:30.626 --> 28:32.794
it was time
to come down on the nigga.

28:32.961 --> 28:35.797
Mr. Kirkland, you know,
it's like smoking.

28:35.964 --> 28:38.007
They got to have
a nigga every 20 minutes.

28:38.175 --> 28:40.468
See, what happened is,

28:40.636 --> 28:43.763
I was in this alley petting my dog
when they came down on me.

28:43.931 --> 28:47.225
It states here that you were...
The dog was attacking you

28:47.393 --> 28:49.268
when you were first seen
in the alley.

28:49.436 --> 28:51.270
Yeah? Yeah, well...

28:51.438 --> 28:53.564
Well, see, my dog,
he gets like that sometimes.

28:53.732 --> 28:56.192
It also states that the dog

28:56.360 --> 28:58.236
belonged to a Mrs. B. Jackson.

29:00.030 --> 29:01.697
Well, he sure looked like my dog.

29:01.865 --> 29:04.575
You know, he had that...
Come on, Ralph.

29:04.743 --> 29:05.910
It also states here

29:06.078 --> 29:09.580
that when asked what you were
doing in the alley,

29:09.748 --> 29:13.960
you replied, "I don't know nothing
about that taxi-cab robbery."

29:14.128 --> 29:15.837
Now, that's true, because I don't.

29:16.880 --> 29:19.340
How'd you know
there was one, Ralph?

29:19.508 --> 29:21.509
Mr. Kirkland, there's always one.

29:21.677 --> 29:25.263
Ralph, tell me the truth
or get another lawyer.

29:25.431 --> 29:28.015
I don't need the bullshit. Let's go.

29:29.309 --> 29:30.810
Okay.

29:31.645 --> 29:33.938
I was in that cab. But I didn't rob it.

29:34.106 --> 29:35.189
It was my cousin's idea.

29:35.357 --> 29:39.735
I didn't know nothing. It was my
cousin's idea. See, he... He crazy.

29:41.864 --> 29:43.781
What's your cousin's name?
I don't know.

29:43.949 --> 29:45.700
I mean...

29:46.702 --> 29:48.035
He live over on Hillsdale.

29:48.203 --> 29:50.204
You don't know
your cousin's name?

29:50.372 --> 29:53.833
Ralph, who do you think
you're talking to?

29:54.042 --> 29:56.669
You think I'm an idiot?
Okay, I read a report,

29:56.837 --> 29:59.922
I can tell if somebody's
bullshitting me or not.

30:00.090 --> 30:01.966
Either you give me
straight answers

30:02.134 --> 30:03.551
or you get another lawyer.

30:03.719 --> 30:08.139
I don't have time to listen
to some jive-ass put me on.

30:08.307 --> 30:09.348
Okay.

30:11.727 --> 30:17.440
It wasn't my idea, but I did
know what was coming down.

30:17.858 --> 30:21.068
See, me and
my cousin Royce...

30:21.737 --> 30:23.988
Royce Shavers.

30:25.073 --> 30:30.912
See, he figures that
since I am the way I am...

30:32.873 --> 30:34.499
Mr. Kirkland,

30:34.666 --> 30:37.418
I can look real fine
sometimes, you know?

30:39.379 --> 30:40.922
Yeah,
I'm sure you can, Ralph.

30:42.674 --> 30:45.801
Well, Royce figures
that we can be a couple.

30:45.969 --> 30:48.179
You know, like a man
and a woman couple.

30:48.347 --> 30:51.432
Because a cab driver will pick
up a couple a whole lot faster

30:51.600 --> 30:54.310
than they will two nigga men.

30:55.103 --> 30:56.437
So, uh...

30:58.732 --> 31:03.027
we got into this cab over
on Garrison Boulevard,

31:04.112 --> 31:06.489
and we asked him to take us down
to the harbor.

31:06.657 --> 31:10.284
You know, like...
Like we was tourists.

31:11.286 --> 31:12.787
And, um...

31:16.542 --> 31:19.752
Hey, man, I...
I can't go to jail, man.

31:19.920 --> 31:23.881
I just can't do it.
I can't go to that place.

31:24.633 --> 31:27.009
Please, Mr. Kirkland,
you've got to help me.

31:27.177 --> 31:33.474
Please.

31:35.102 --> 31:36.143
Okay.
Please.

31:36.311 --> 31:39.647
Okay, I'll help you, Ralph.
Just don't lie to me, that's all.

31:39.982 --> 31:42.441
Okay? Okay.
Yes, sir.

31:45.112 --> 31:47.655
Thank you.
Don't lie to me. Okay?

31:47.823 --> 31:49.657
Yes, sir.
Okay.

31:49.825 --> 31:51.158
Thank you.

31:52.953 --> 31:55.204
[GAIL & ARTHUR LAUGHING]

31:59.668 --> 32:01.669
ARTHUR:
Thanks for bringing me home, Gail.

32:01.837 --> 32:04.171
[BOTH LAUGHING]

32:05.173 --> 32:07.049
Oh, God.

32:07.217 --> 32:09.010
Well...

32:09.177 --> 32:12.513
You really take renting
an unfurnished apartment
literally, don't you?

32:13.015 --> 32:15.349
Arthur, you know it doesn't
have to stay this way.

32:17.811 --> 32:18.894
What happened?

32:19.062 --> 32:22.023
Did your wife take you
in the divorce settlement?

32:22.524 --> 32:25.484
She had a better lawyer.
Oh.

32:27.029 --> 32:29.488
What about your kids?
Get to see them much?

32:29.656 --> 32:31.490
Well, they're in California,
you know.

32:31.658 --> 32:34.285
Phone calls, holidays.

32:34.995 --> 32:37.538
Put the food out,
I'll get the plates.

32:37.873 --> 32:41.709
I guess I was lucky.
We never had any kids.

32:41.877 --> 32:45.171
How long were you married?
Three years.

32:45.422 --> 32:49.133
Were you in love?
No.

32:49.509 --> 32:52.053
I was in love with the law.

32:52.638 --> 32:54.597
You know what I mean?

32:56.642 --> 32:58.184
Got a serving spoon?

32:59.561 --> 33:01.395
Serving spoon.

33:02.731 --> 33:03.939
Thank you.

33:05.901 --> 33:08.611
So, uh, you eat out a lot?

33:08.779 --> 33:09.904
Yeah, you?

33:10.072 --> 33:11.322
Yeah.

33:12.449 --> 33:15.159
The committee works
just about every night.

33:17.204 --> 33:20.247
How did you feel when you walked
out on the committee this morning?

33:20.415 --> 33:22.500
Did you feel all those daggers
in your back?

33:22.668 --> 33:25.127
That's a very
dangerous group, you know?

33:25.295 --> 33:26.837
Jesus.

33:27.005 --> 33:28.798
Here we go, here we go.

33:28.965 --> 33:31.342
Arthur, why?

33:31.510 --> 33:34.053
Why do you feel
it's dangerous?

33:34.221 --> 33:37.515
Because you're conning
the public into thinking
you're doing something.

33:37.683 --> 33:40.017
And you're not.
Yeah. But we are doing something.

33:40.185 --> 33:41.894
No.
We are protecting the public

33:42.062 --> 33:45.064
from a lot of corrupt lawyers,
is what we're doing.

33:45.816 --> 33:49.026
You're skimming the surface.
You're not going after
real power.

33:49.194 --> 33:51.112
[WHISTLES]

33:51.780 --> 33:55.574
Wow. That's scary.
What real power, Arthur?

33:55.742 --> 33:58.119
You don't know?
No, why don't you tell me?

33:58.286 --> 34:01.706
Well, now we know
they're definitely safe.

34:05.335 --> 34:08.713
What makes you think
you know so goddamn much?

34:09.630 --> 34:11.674
I don't know so much.
No, no. Tell me.

34:11.842 --> 34:14.301
What makes you the great
voice of authority?

34:14.469 --> 34:15.969
[CHUCKLES]

34:16.221 --> 34:19.556
I don't pretend to be
a voice of authority.

34:23.853 --> 34:26.938
It's just, I don't think
you know what you're doing,
that's all.

34:27.190 --> 34:30.484
Oh, I see. Yeah, yeah.

34:32.571 --> 34:35.322
This is nice,
don't you think?

34:35.489 --> 34:38.242
No, I don't find this
particularly nice.

34:38.409 --> 34:40.619
Arthur, I'm, um...

34:43.165 --> 34:45.206
I'm angry again.

34:45.375 --> 34:47.333
You know? I don't like being angry.

34:47.502 --> 34:49.420
It's not pleasant.
I don't understand

34:49.588 --> 34:52.005
how you can criticize me
for what I do.

34:52.507 --> 34:55.842
I'm not criticizing you, Gail.
I mean, you're taking it
too personally.

34:56.011 --> 34:59.847
Arthur, the committee is doing
something about what's going on.

35:00.015 --> 35:03.768
We are not sitting in jail at nights
because of contempt of court.

35:05.353 --> 35:07.563
Do you know what that's about?
Yeah.

35:07.731 --> 35:10.649
Yeah?
You threw a punch at Judge Fleming.

35:10.817 --> 35:14.361
Uh-huh. You know why?
I have no idea. Tell me.

35:14.654 --> 35:18.532
I got a client who's in jail
because of a faulty taillight

35:18.700 --> 35:20.159
and I can't get him out.

35:20.327 --> 35:22.578
What do you mean
you can't get him out?

35:22.746 --> 35:26.165
You wanna hear a story
about our wonderful judicial system?

35:26.333 --> 35:28.959
Hm?
Sure.

35:29.419 --> 35:31.212
There's a guy named
Jeff McCullaugh,

35:31.379 --> 35:34.590
and he's going down
the highway one night

35:35.217 --> 35:39.220
and the cops stop him
because his taillight isn't working.

35:39.387 --> 35:41.764
They pull him over to the side,
run a make on him.

35:41.932 --> 35:45.601
Computer kicks back
that there's a Jeff McCullaugh

35:45.769 --> 35:48.687
wanted in Alabama
for assault with a deadly weapon.

35:48.855 --> 35:50.731
Was this the same Jeff McCullaugh?
No.

35:50.899 --> 35:54.026
But he fits
the general description
so they arrest him.

35:54.194 --> 35:56.862
Why didn't McCullaugh tell them
they had the wrong person?

35:57.030 --> 36:00.115
He told the public defender,
who I don't think really believed him.

36:00.283 --> 36:01.700
And he was too busy.

36:01.868 --> 36:04.787
He never even bothered to check.
Are you serious?

36:05.288 --> 36:07.414
Ah, wait. It gets better.

36:07.916 --> 36:13.045
While Jeff is sitting in jail,
a guard is stabbed.

36:13.213 --> 36:16.006
And the knife is planted
in Jeff's cell.

36:16.174 --> 36:18.801
And Jeff is brought to trial
on a new charge,

36:18.969 --> 36:22.054
this time, assaulting a guard
with a deadly weapon.

36:22.222 --> 36:24.765
And a trial date is set

36:24.933 --> 36:28.435
six months from the time
he was first picked up.

36:30.021 --> 36:32.982
I'll make a long story short for you.
Six months go by

36:33.149 --> 36:37.152
and a very shaky, very crazy
Jeff McCullaugh goes to court.

36:37.320 --> 36:40.573
Now, the public defender
who's defending him, he says...

36:40.740 --> 36:44.243
He tells Jeff that he can get him off
Mm-hm.

36:44.411 --> 36:45.452
If he pleads guilty.

36:45.620 --> 36:48.205
He'll make a deal with the judge,
and he'll get him off.

36:48.373 --> 36:49.456
Time served.
Right.

36:49.624 --> 36:51.750
So he pleads guilty
even though he's innocent.

36:51.918 --> 36:55.462
That's right. However,
the deal was made
with a Judge Callahan.

